{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"59bc11ba-9c9a-4d48-af5e-bc35232f2610","content":"A **NullReferenceException** is an application-level bug (a null variable being dereferenced), not a CLR activation issue. CLR activation logs diagnose problems like the wrong runtime version loading or the runtime failing to start at all — they won't help find a null reference in your code.\n\nHere's what will actually help:\n\n1. **Read the stack trace** — it tells you the exact line where the null dereference happens.\n2. **Check the object on that line** — figure out why it's null (missing initialization, failed dependency injection, race condition, etc.).\n3. **Use a debugger** — attach with Visual Studio or `dotnet-dump` to inspect state.\n\nIf you share the **exception message and stack trace**, I can help pinpoint the bug. Do you have that output?","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"7633c43a-ba16-4f4b-ae11-52ddc6286203","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about analyzing CLR activation logs to diagnose a NullReferenceException in their .NET app. They mention CLR activation logs specifically, which relates to .NET Framework CLR activation/loading issues.\n\nI have a skill available called \"clr-activation-debugging\" which is specifically designed for diagnosing .NET Framework CLR activation issues using CLR activation logs. Let me invoke that skill.\n\nHowever, I should note that a NullReferenceException is typically an application-level bug, not a CLR activation issue. CLR activation logs deal with which runtime version gets loaded, not with application exceptions. But the user specifically asked about CLR activation logs, so let me invoke the skill and let it guide the conversation.","outputTokens":357,"requestId":"1B86:2BCA1C:1594946:18266A5:6A028349"},"id":"0a836bed-0b89-4481-892f-1d5d5c7756fb","timestamp":"2026-05-12T01:33:09.080Z","parentId":"c0fe64a3-83cf-4bcd-924a-9009dfe7d3d3"}
